<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="63" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="63">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="63">
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. D. Tovar" authorityYear="2022" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum bohsii" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bohsii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">Solanum bohsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from three localities in the western slopes of the central Andean cordillera in Colombia in the Departments of Caldas, Quindio and Risaralda (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Distribution of Solanum bohsii J. D. Tovar (yellow stars)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.195.78832.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681517" pageId="0" pageNumber="63">3</figureCitation>
) where it inhabits secondary forest edges between 1,900-2,300 m elevation, forming groups of up to 10 individuals.
</paragraph>
